\section{Introduction}
Superconductivity is a phenomenon in which the electrical resistance of a material drops to zero below a critical temperature. The Meissner effect, which is the complete expulsion of magnetic fields from the interior of a superconductor, is a consequence of the perfect diamagnetism exhibited by superconductors. The magnetic field lines are forced to travel around the superconductor, creating a shielding effect. However, when a magnetic field is applied to a superconductor, the flux lines can penetrate the material and cause the superconducting properties to degrade. This phenomenon is known as flux pinning and has been extensively studied in the context of low-temperature superconductors. 

In recent years, the discovery of high-temperature superconductors has opened up new possibilities for practical applications, particularly in the field of energy transmission technology. High-temperature superconductors exhibit superconducting properties at temperatures much higher than those of low-temperature superconductors. However, the phenomenon of flux pinning remains a challenge for the development of high-capacity superconductors. 

One of the proposed mechanisms for flux pinning in high-temperature superconductors is quantum flux pinning, which occurs when the magnetic flux lines are quantized due to the small size of the superconductor. The quantization of flux lines leads to a discrete set of energy levels, which can affect the superconducting properties of the material. In this study, we propose an experimental approach to investigate the effect of quantum flux pinning in high-temperature superconductors.

